segments.text: on the backside there.
Oh, I see.
And that's the way the thing worked.
And I kept going on.
Taking courses.
Taking courses.
Now, were these basically correspondence courses?
These were correspondence courses.
That's correct.
up until, here's the order, sending me to Fort Sill for 90 days to take what they call a battery officer's course.
And when was that?
This is September 16, 1938.
Well, I was interested in qualifying myself.
I was given a second lieutenant's commission when I got out of A&M.
But I finished with certain grade points in ROTC.
And I got interested in associating with these people as a second lieutenant.
And we went down to Fort Sam, or out to Camp Bullis, for our two weeks active training.
Sure.
Every summer?
Every summer.
I didn't miss a summer until I went to Fort Sill in 1940, permanently.
I was qualifying myself and I could see myself progressing.
I was getting something out of it and having a lot of fun with it.
And so I, at that time I was a bachelor and just something to tie into and do.
And I did.
And here's where I got my certificate of capacity to a captain.
And he followed this whole thing right to
Here's another one of our OTC officers down there.
He finally made General Officer Aldridge Squirrel Tooth Aldridge.
That's where he was telling me that they had sent my promotion, recommendation, a motion to a captain to the War Department.
Here's where I was promoted to Captain in the Reserves, effective July 26, 1939.
Would you consider giving these personal papers eventually to the archives at Texas A&M?
Well, when I die, I will them to them.
Certainly not now.
I haven't thought about it.
The archivist, who is my boss, would be very happy to have these in the permanent collection.
They only pertain to me and the others that are on the same orders.
But that's exactly what we're after.
That's what archives do, collect personal papers.
And of course,
I was wondering about the conditions inside the reserve units.
Did you men get paid for being a reservist then?
We got paid in the sense that when we went to active duty, we got second lieutenant and first lieutenants paid for fourteen days.
And they paid our transportation down and back.
You didn't get paid for any weekend assignments or any week, every Thursday night?
Every Thursday night, no.
All you do is you've got credit for doing that correspondence work.
And ultimately, you were rewarded, certainly not in the concept of the thing at that time, but
You built up longevity by time.
Every Thursday night was one point.
This is something that came along later, and we had no conception of it at that time.
And this has all come about, I guess, after the war of active duty points in calculating retirement.
And I guess the Reserve Officers Association had
much impact on it of influencing the army that set the system up to give credit for those inactive days.
Because in calculating my retirement pay, I got credit for those Thursday nights and those two weeks that we went to camp.
Then it was unknown, but it was a recognition.
This came about after the Second World War, but before that it was unknown.
That's right, it was unknown.
In other words, you were not doing it.
There was no real financial benefit whatsoever for being in the reserves.
No.
Like there is today.
No.
Here's my order to call them to active duty.
I'm just looking at this thing.
Okay, you were called to active duty in what, 1940?
Yeah, December 29, 1940.
And Appy was, just looking at these now, Appy was Oklahoma A&M boy, Oklahoma University.
Fanning
was, I think, Oklahoma.
Fleet was A&M.
Jim Kerr was A&M.
Kidd was A&M.
And Kendrick was A&M.
So four out of six on that order were Texas A&M.
Artillerymen.
Those were all artillery.
All of us went up to Fort Sill together.
What were your feelings when you were called into the active duty in 1940?
Well, I was working, had a job, and my feelings were that because of the national or international situation, Hitler was running a merc that
Our very stability of our country was at stake, and it was my job to go do what I could.
I was happy for the qualification I had, meaning I had prepared myself now.
I didn't know what I was preparing for, but I was preparing myself, in that I could do a better job for them.
I was obsessed with the fact that I was going to defend my country.
I felt that I could do a better job for my training.
And back then, I couldn't put it in those words.
I knew what I was trying to do of keeping current and qualifying myself if it ever happened.
Well, when I got disordered, it did happen.
And I am unqualified, unequivocally, you can say,
that my training at A&M and my commission out of A&M gave me some breaks by Army officers that had been associated with A&M officers.
And you got a break by being an A&M cadet or A&M officer.
What do you mean?
Can you give me an example of a break?
What do you mean by a break?
Well.
They treated you better?
No, you got a chance to.
They gave you a responsibility.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
And you got a chance to demonstrate your capabilities.
Okay.
I went up to Fort Seal in December 1940 and got assigned to, because of my rank, I was given a,
a battery and school troops which do all the maneuvering and firing for the students there.
And I stayed there about four months, five months, and then they had set up the replacement training center, artillery replacement training center.
We trained
We trained initial trainees and replacements.
And the break I'm talking about is that because I was an A&M civil engineer, I was put in command by an old army colonel who had been associated with A&M cadets on this reserve training plane.
And everyone that came in his command,
He grabbed him and he personally assigned him.
And he looked at my 66-1, which is your personnel record card, this pink card here.
And he looked at that and saw Texas A&M, civil engineer.
And he said, Kidwell commands the instrument and survey battery.
As such, we
got all of the college graduates, draftees, who were engineers.
And I taught them, my battery's job was to teach them artillery survey.
Operating a plane table, operating a BC scope, operating a transit to survey in
Sure.
The artillery.
And so that's the first thing that you did?
That was the first thing after I got moved over there from this school troop battery.
So this is the type of break that you're talking about?
This is the type of break.
In other words, he's given you an opportunity to prove, to make or break yourself.
He gave me the opportunity to prove
Because I wasn't getting the average draftee.
I was getting all college boys or college graduates.
If a draftee came in and he was studying any kind of engineering, he came to my battery.
Because we were teaching them something.
We taught them to figure firing data off of a slide rule, for instance.
And a slide rule was brand new at that time.
There were no calculators, but there were slide rules.
And we taught them to figure firing data with slide rule.
Well, to figure firing data, you got to know logarithms.
And he came right on back to his college training seat.
I got the finest soldiers that came in the Army and were assigned to the artillery.
They came in my battery.
And I made qualified
capable soldiers out of them.
And they went out and did their job.
And because of that, I consistently got superior ratings on the type of soldier we were turning out, notwithstanding the fact that we had a high caliber person to start with.
And some of them come on the other side of the tracks, and some of them come out of Brooklyn.
Cross section of life.
But I got the top of the cream.
And I was able to mold those people into where every one of them were proficient when they left there.
And we didn't have any discipline troubles.
I mean, they wanted to do.
They came in to learn something.
And we gave it to them.
And they went out and did their job.
And that was our job to teach them.
It was a good job.
I had lots of fun with it, and I enjoyed it because I could see my accomplishments.
How many did you teach?
Tell me how it was set up.
How long it was set up?
Yeah.
How long was the school?
How was it set up?
Well, they were there basically 12 weeks.
They ran through a 12-week cycle.
Okay.
And we had them three months.
And, of course, the more proficient ones we'd send out in 10 weeks if they got a
emergency requisition, they called it, a hurry-up call.
Some outfit going overseas and they needed an instrument survey man or they needed a fire direction center man.
We'd take the cream, the most astute student, the most applicable student, and learn the fastest.
We'd give him a cram course at night and send him out.
And this is something that
Never been done in the Army before.
Is this because of the war, then?
Well, this was because of the emergency.
It had to be accelerated because of the war, then?
No, it had to be accelerated.
We were given a man 12 weeks.
And then we would have an emergency requisition because of some of them going to the Far East.
I see.
And then is when I took the attitude of having this night training also.
to give him a cram course.
And of course, it couldn't help it but be recognized by my battalion commander and my artillery commander.
What did they think?
Well, they liked the way it was progressing.
And they kept up very close to it.
And that's the break that I got because of this.
See, I did an outstanding job with that battery.
And I got to go to the field officer's course.
The colonel, my regimental commander, got a requisition for two students to go to the field officer's course, which means qualifying you for a field officer, meaning a major or higher grade.
And he had seen the work I'd done over there, and he knew that I'd go do a good job.
He didn't want to send somebody over there that would bust the thing.
It wouldn't be outstanding.
Because his recommendations reflected on him.
Couldn't help it.
So he sent me as one of his recommended students, and I went over there.
And I stood high in the academic class.
Well, that's on the 66-1.
And because of that,
The next time, while I was at the field officer course, I got promoted to major.
I don't remember when that was, but I got it.
And that made you the battalion executive officer of the 8th Training Regiment?
Yeah.
When you were promoted to major?
Yeah, I was, I got promoted to major and
Major, 20th of June, 1942.
Okay, okay.
I was in the Army 18 months.
Here it is, 19th of June, 1942.
Here's my... 19th of June?
That's what it says here.
It says 20th here.
Well, wait a minute.
It's dated.
It may be dated as of...
Well, there it is.
You weren't even a major a year before you were promoted to about ten months, and then you were promoted to lieutenant colonel.
How can you account for that?
That's an incredibly fast promotion.
I'll tell you about that.
But here's the 19th of June, and this is my promotion order.
Okay, I'll just cross this off then.
Date of rank is date of this order, unless otherwise specified, indicated after name.
I'll put 19th.
19th, yeah.
So that's 19th of June.
And it says date of this date.
But anyway.
How can you account for the fact that you were only a major 10 months?
Well, I'll tell you.
There again was a break, two breaks, and having been recognized, every job they gave me as a major, I did and excelled in it.
And what job?
The job was battalion executive officer, right?
Battalion executive officer, and I believe I was S3 at part of the time.
The S3, yeah, operations.
Operations officer, and I was a summary court martial and all the added inspector jobs that you get.
So what were your functions then as the battalion XO?
Well, as battalion exec, you carry out the...
battalion commander's orders or see if they're carried out.
You do all the checking for him.
He's the man who makes the decision, but you get him the information.
And you check on your battery commanders.
And you check his messes.
You check his supplies.
You check the bookkeeping.
It's an executive job, meaning you do whatever the battalion commander desires, and you have no command.
You have no command, but you are a representing commander, if that's a good way to put it.
Okay, fine, fine.
And there are your, the function of course of the battalion, was training there, artillery training.
Your battalion S3 is your playing and training officer.
As such, you have to get up the
battalion training programs and see that your battery commanders have got their lesson plans for a certain lesson on a certain day.
And you coordinate all the training and inspection of that training.
And that eminently qualifies you from a training viewpoint.
before you can inspect it or set it up, you've got to do it yourself.
Absolutely.
Now how many men, I know this is a difficult question, but here we are in 1942, approximately how many men were we training?
Or in training?
Yeah, how many young officers, most of these are second lieutenants, right, that you're training to be artillery officers?
How many are in each class, or how did that work?

Well, we were training them basically as instrument survey people, meaning battery fire direction centers, your battery surveyors and battalion surveyors, and your battalion fire direction people, which are all engineering jobs.
And I commanded that battery for 18 months, and gosh, we ran through 250 on a 12-week cycle, three-month cycle.
So we...
Okay, so every class, and it was 250, and it was 12 weeks.
Yeah, 12 weeks, that's right.
Okay, that's basically what I wanted to know then.
That would be 18 divided by 3.
If 12 weeks makes 3 months, it would be 6 times 250, 1,500 people.
So you were really keeping them moving through there.
Had to, had to.
Sure, you were, yeah.
And I had to stay one jump ahead of them.
Yeah.
Believe you me.
I was out there before they ever got up in the morning.
I stayed until after we put them to bed every night, looking after my people, purely and simply looking after my people.
And I tell you, looking after your people means to me, means seeing that everything goes right for them.
For instance, one time I went out there at about 4.30 in the morning to check on the breakfast.
The cooks had come in drunk that night before, 1.30 to 2 o'clock.
going on to bed and sleeping and having a charge of quarters wake them up at 4.30 or 5 whenever they were supposed to get up.
They cooked all the breakfast, eggs, made the biscuits and everything, fried eggs.
Then they went to sleep.
And I got there about 4.30, a quarter to 5, and saw all these cold fried eggs.
And I went in and asked my charge of quarter, what the hell is happening?
He didn't know.
He said he knew the cooks were in there.
He thought they were getting just preparatory work or something.
He didn't know they cooked breakfast.
Well, when I saw what happened, I went in and told his first sergeant what happened by that time he was up and around.
And I told him to go ahead with Reveille and tell the men that breakfast would be late.
And they'll go on about their chores.
They'll clean up the barracks, do the police work and everything.
We'd have breakfast at 7.30 so there could be a train at 8 o'clock.
Well, of course, this so happened that the colonel drove through the area that morning checking Reveille.
And we were, our schedule instead of being breakfast and all was also upset because it's breakfast business.
And he stopped and came wanting to know what the hell was happening with my schedule.
And I told him.
And he says, I got it, Kidwell.
I'm glad to see you're here.
And I'm glad to know that you know that an army travels on their stomachs.
Kidwell, he says, very early in life, and I'll give you the same lesson.
If you give a man a good breakfast, he'll do you a good day's work.
What?
This is kind of bricks that I'm talking about.
Sure, really.
I impressed that old man.
And so you're talking about being a major and why I was promoted to lieutenant colonel in a hurry.
That was so fast, yeah.
Why did they shift you to Fort Meade, Maryland?
Well, wait a minute.
Which was your second, which was after you left Fort Sill.
Then you went to Maryland.
Chronologically, you're skipping here.
I don't know the notes that you have, but chronologically.
This is what I got from your Westmoreland letter.
Oh, well, yeah, there's a lot that I've left out.
Oh, okay.
I'm looking, I'm just thumbing through orders here now.
You bet.
Let me stop here.
I'm looking for order here.
Because of a lot of instances like this breakfast deal that I reiterated,
Incidentally, what did you do to those cooks?
I busted all of them and transferred them out on the next requisition for people.
They had a cook's battery up there also.
Here's what I was looking for.
They had a cook's battery that taught
raw recruits, Army cooking.
And there again, it's 12 weeks.
And the first time they got a requisition for some more men, well, I said, I'm going to mess all those cooks out on that requisition, because they were qualified cooks.
They just goofed up once.
They just got drunk and goofed up, and they had the wrong battery commander, as far as I was concerned.
And I got rid of them.
I busted them and shipped them out.
The rail break that I got because of that cooking and lots of other instances like that.
But on January 24, I got ordered to command and general staff school at Leavenworth.
I don't remember whether that's in that thing or not.
DAVID BURRAGE.
January 1943, yeah.
OK, I got it right up there.
And why did they send you?
To go to school.
Yeah, but why you instead of somebody else?
Because my regimental commander made the recommendation and sold it to the general that we worked for.
And there again, he wanted to send somebody that he knew damn well would go up there and make a credible record.
And I had impressed him with his breakfast business.
As soon as I got going as a battery commander, you know, a battery earns money, dividends from post-exchange profits.
And they give it to you.
You can spend it on anything you want to spend it on, as long as for the benefit of all the men in that battery.
Well, our mess hall up there was just a dismal,
two before mess hall.
And I got the idea of decorating it up.
So I lined it with plywood and we painted it, as I remember, a soft green color.
And it made a pleasant place to eat.
And that was certainly a legitimate expenditure of post-exchange money.
And an old man come by to inspect my mess and he saw all this work going on.
He asked about it, and I told him what I was doing.
He said, that's fine, that's fine.
And he came back, and before it all over, why, half the mess halls up there were done that way, because those commanders would come by and see mine that way.
Of course, they got to the general, and he commented about it, and they admired it.
Well, all the rest of them wanted to do their same way, and that kind of thing.
Another thing, they had sand and ultimately dirt
walks up there.
That's the way the camp was constructed.

I knew something about concrete and there again we had this money so with my battery carpenter who did all the farm work and then we just got some people to help us if we wanted to, we poured concrete walks in the whole area.
Well they did two things when they were going to the mess in the inclement weather, they
their shines from getting messed up, kept mud off their feet, meaning they didn't track mud back into barracks and have to mop it again and all these kind of things.
But old man saw that too.
And I was always doing something like that to better take care of my soldiers.
Wow.
Okay.
So he sent you up here?
So he sent me to... And tell me about Command and General Staff School.
Up at Command and General Staff School in January 1943.
I had a good friend that went up there and came back in Class 11.
I was in General Staff School 12, Class 12.
It was an accelerated...
wartime course of 90 days.
And my friend was a school teacher, artilleryman.
He had a company or battery next to mine.
And we visited over a cup of coffee, our mutual problems in our areas, this kind of thing.
And he went, he was there ahead of me.
He came back and he said, now, Graber,
I'm going to tell you how to get along up there.
And I said, fine.
That's what I'm interested in.
There's two things you've got to do.
You've got to study meticulously and keep your eyes and ears open during all the lectures, all lecture discussions.
And I had some class participation, the basics of the lecture.
They give you problems work, get out at nighttime, and you come back.
They call on students to give their solutions to them in this country.
You keep your eyes and ears open and take meticulous notes in the classroom.
And as soon as you eat supper, you go back and start studying until 10 o'clock.
And you go to bed and go to sleep.
So the next day, you'll be alert and keep your eyes and ears open, take my notes.
And then he pointed out one thing.
He says that whenever they repeat something in your notes, you underline it, because it's coming back on pay quiz.
They call them pay quizzes, on a test.
And I meticulously did what he told me.
I don't have it now, but I had all those books alphabetically listed, or indexed, so I could turn to the reference data like that.
And you could use any manuals, any Army manuals you wanted on examination.
Because the theory is, if you didn't know where to look for it, I mean, if you didn't know it, you didn't know where to look for it.
And I had them all indexed like that.
So if they wanted the train length of a quartermaster battalion, I could go to cues, and I had it in two or three seconds.
and that gave me time to do something else and I had to stop and think about it.
So you were extraordinarily well organized.
I was well organized because the school teacher friend was there ahead of me and he told me what to do.
And why I got promoted to lieutenant colonel so fast is I went up there and excelled again.
You can't get away from that, excelling.
I stood number 11 in a class of
Over 800.
Number, but that's tremendous.
Number 11.
And the reason I did it, they gave you these quizzes all, I don't know, once a week, once every two weeks, on particular subject, depending on how long the subject was.
And then they give you a month quiz or six weeks quiz when they finish that subject, you know.
And as I remember, I made all As but two, and they were Bs.
And the first 10 probably made all As, I don't know.
Or they made a better A than mine.
As I remember, the A grade was 95 to 100, and B was 85 to 95, and C was 70 to 85, and below C was a U, if you didn't make it.
70 or 75, it was unsatisfactory.
And I made all A's but two.
Their A's may have been higher than mine, or they may have made A while I made a B.
But anyway.
But you did quite well.
I was 11th, which is outstanding.
Well, there again, that gets on the 66-1 scene.
Sure.
And when the general, this is the first introduction you get to when you're
you're assigned to his command, is you get this, this goes ahead of you.
And he'll take it, or his, his exec, chief of staff will take it, and they'll go through here.
That same old kid went to the NG&R course in 38, he went to field officer's course and did so well in 42, and he did so well up at the CNGS, he's 11.
in his class at CNJS in 43.
Well, that earmarked me and gave me breaks.
That's all a word you can say about it, gave me some breaks.
Now, during this school, this command staff college, during this, what did they teach you?
They teach you tactics and wartime tactics and strategies.
strategic planning and tactical planning, pretty much anything.
A.T. taught me how to maneuver armies and divisions and artillery groups as a commander.
Tactics and strategies.
So this would help, of course, this would help you get promotion too because they'd need somebody on the battlefield with this knowledge.
That's right.
There's no question about that.
Okay.
That equips you to do their job.
And, you know, a tactical commander has a tremendous responsibility.
Sure, absolutely.
And he doesn't want an average person doing his command down below him.
He wants to be able to call in a half dozen top flight commanders and say, I want this, or this is what we're going to do, and this is your job.
And he doesn't want somebody stubbing their toe because it reflects on him.
He's looking for four stars instead of three or something like this.
And if they flub their dub down here in this operation, it's on his 66-1, not mine.
You can't offer excuses on this thing, see.
It's just cold turkey.
And he's looking for somebody that he thinks can carry the ball.
And this, after you had this school, then you were sent as the CO?
Is that what happened next in the progression?
You were sent as the CO, 17th Field Artillery Battalion, Fort Meade, Maryland?
No, no.
The next thing that happened, and I'll tell you this, I'm here today talking to you by a good friend of mine trying to,
Rook me, you know.
I won't say the word on that.
He got out of Leavenworth.
He and I were classmates up there.
Mark Tellerman.
And he came back and he didn't do so hot.
So they put him over in personnel.
And he didn't like that worth a damn.
Of course, we're just in a holding station.
After you get out of Leavenworth, they send you out to a senior
unit meaning division or a major unit.
Because you've got to train to do the job, as far as the Army's concerned, and they send you out there.
And I had a very, well, General Potter, when he saw that I was 11 in class, he said, damn kid, well that's great, that's great.
He said, I'll have you a job here some of these days real quick now that you'll like.
Because he's always getting requisitions from the War Department for an officer of a certain caliber, of a certain training level.
And I saw him one day at the officer club at lunch.
He said, kiddo, I recommend you for a job today.
You get your bags packed, boy, because you're gone.
Where am I going, gentlemen?
Where am I going?
Well, that don't make any difference.
You just get your bags packed.
See, I saw him a week later and said, General, I got my bags packed.
I'm still around.
He says, Well, this is a stole.
Hold tight.
Just keep your bitches on.
I think he told me.
And so I stayed there two, three, four more days.
I saw him again over at the office a couple of nights.
He said, I thought you were gone.
I'm waiting on some orders.
He says, well, I saw some orders for you to go yesterday.
I'm by the office when I get back.
And this is all in retrospect now, what happened.
And he told me what, he would never tell me the job before that, then he told me.
What happened was this friend of mine in personnel
The general sent my name up there to go on this order.
It was a top secret deal.
And he could see himself getting out of this country in a matter of 24 hours.
He inserted his name for my name.
Notwithstanding the fact that he didn't foresee the ultimate damage that could be done to his army career or his career.
Because if they'd ever caught it, and they'd have caught it sooner or later, well, they'd have crucified him.
But anyway.
Did they catch him?
The answer is no.
Why not?
How could they not catch him?
OK.
The general knew you were supposed to go.
That's right.
He went up to Andrews Air Force Base and got with this group of officers.
They were in a plane going to Portugal to stage
on a top secret mission going in to lay in the man work for the American Army to go into North Africa.
His plane went down three or four miles off of Portugal and they were all lost.
So you were lucky.
So I'm alive today because that son of a bitch tried to, well did, rip me.
But the job was, General Potter told me later, that I was going to be the artillery

representative with General Clark, Mark Clark, went into North Africa in a submarine with a bunch of gold and all to get with the Free French and set up the Free French to give us a place to land in North Africa.
And that whole kit and caboodle was lost because the airplane went down.
And of course, General Clark was already there in Portugal, and that's just one of those things.
But I'm here today because he did that.
Well, anyway, that fizzled.
That fizzled.
That definitely fizzled.
That fizzled as far as I was concerned.
It made a good way for you.
Yeah, that's right, as far as I was concerned.
That fizzled, but then I went up to Fort Meade.
Okay, as the CO of the 17th Field Artillery Division.
Yeah.
As a lieutenant colonel.
As a lieutenant colonel.
I was promoted lieutenant colonel on April 6, 1943.
And when did you arrive there at Fort Meade?
Well, I'll tell you.
Probably about the same time.
A little later.
There's another school I went to.
I don't know whether that's on my mind.
But I went to Tanker Star School.
It was four batteries, typical artillery battalion.
I went up there in July of 43.
Approximately how many men and how much artillery?
Well, a battalion is four batteries, approximately
100 to 110 or 15 men, about 425 men total.
How much artillery?
Well, you've got three gun batteries and headquarters battery, 12 guns, and that's standard battery.
OK. And what did you do it for at Meaden?
We did training work.
Oh, training work.
A big part?
More training.
More training work.
A similar job to what you had at Fort Sullivan.
That's exactly correct.
We were on a training mission.
